these limits prevent "Resource Temporarily Unavailable" errors (forking issues) and "Too Many Open Files" during high-load Oracle operations.
Add these lines to /etc/security/limits.conf (or a dedicated file in /etc/security/limits.d/):
Recommended Limits for Oracle & Grid Users

# --- ORACLE USER LIMITS ---
oracle   soft   nofile    1024
oracle   hard   nofile    65536
oracle   soft   nproc     16384
oracle   hard   nproc     16384
oracle   soft   stack     10240
oracle   hard   stack     32768
oracle   soft   memlock   unlimited
oracle   hard   memlock   unlimited
oracle   soft   data      unlimited
oracle   hard   data      unlimited

# --- GRID USER LIMITS (For Clusterware) ---
grid     soft   nofile    1024
grid     hard   nofile    65536
grid     soft   nproc     16384
grid     hard   nproc     16384
grid     soft   stack     10240
grid     hard   stack     32768


Why these specific values?

memlock set to unlimited: This is mandatory if you are using HugePages. It allows the Oracle process to "lock" its SGA in physical RAM so it never gets swapped to disk.
nproc (Processes): With 46 cores and a RAC setup, Oracle spawns many background processes (LMS, PMON, DBWn) plus parallel query slaves. Setting this to 16,384 prevents the OS Error: 11 (Resource temporarily unavailable) when the system is busy.
nofile (Open Files): Oracle opens many datafiles, redo logs, and trace files simultaneously. A low limit here causes the database to crash or hang during I/O-intensive tasks.
stack: Oracle recommends at least 10MB (10240) to prevent stack overflow errors during complex PL/SQL executions.

Verification Step

After saving the file, you must re-log in as the oracle user for these to take effect. Verify them by running:

su - oracle
ulimit -Sa   # Check Soft limits
ulimit -Ha   # Check Hard limits

For a deep dive into why these are required, refer to the Oracle Database Installation Guide for Linux.

To calculate the exact vm.nr_hugepages for your 80GB RAM server, you must match the total SGA size of all running Oracle instances to the available HugePage pool. 


1. The Core Formula
The standard calculation for Linux (where the default Hugepagesize is 2MB) is: 

vm.nr_hugepages = (Total SGA size in MB / 2 MB) + a small buffer (e.g., 5–10 pages) 

