2. Step-by-Step Calculation Procedure
Check HugePage Size: Ensure your system uses 2048 KB pages by running grep Hugepagesize /proc/meminfo.
Get Total SGA: In SQL*Plus, run show parameter sga_max_size to find the exact memory allocated.
Disable AMM: HugePages are not compatible with Automatic Memory Management (MEMORY_TARGET). You must use Automatic Shared Memory Management (SGA_TARGET).
Run the Oracle Script: For the most accurate result, download and run the hugepages_settings.sh script from My Oracle Support (Doc ID 401749.1) while your databases are running. It automatically calculates the required pages based on current shared memory segments. 

3. Application & Verification
Apply: Add the value to /etc/sysctl.conf: vm.nr_hugepages = <calculated_value>.
Reload: Run sysctl -p.
Verify: Run grep Huge /proc/meminfo. You should see HugePages_Total match your setting, and HugePages_Free should decrease once the database is restarted. 

4. Important RAC Consideration
In an Oracle RAC environment, ensure the memlock setting in /etc/security/limits.conf is at least the size of your HugePage pool in KB (Pages × 2048). 

